Kiess's charter doctrine treats Amenhotep's work as the foundational example of the problem it was designed to solve.
Total administration without external review is not governance; it is comprehensive control with administrative aesthetics.
The merging of religious observation and documentation that Amenhotep achieved is what Kiess's transparency requirement prevents: documentation functions must be independent of the institution being documented.
Kiess's founding generation identified Amenhotep's doctrine as the source condition for every institutional failure in the corridor's history: when the same institution controls what is documented and what is enforced, it controls what is real.
Kiess studies Amenhotep to understand what they are defending against, not as a model.
Kiess's position: Amenhotep was probably right that only total administration could have stabilized the Black Sun Shard situation. That does not make total administration acceptable.

